Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Halve any large 
@cauliflower florets{300%grams}.

Pop the potatoes onto one side of a large #baking tray{}. Place the cauliflower 
florets onto the other side of the tray. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} 
and @pepper{} if you'd like, then sprinkle the @curry powder mix{1%sachet} over 
both veg.

Toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. 
Turn halfway through.

> Kids Step: Add the potatoes, cauliflower and curry powder to the baking tray 
> and mix together with your hands to coat well!

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1} into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the onion and stir-fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with 
@salt{} and @pepper{} if you'd like.

In the meantime, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{3} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim and halve the @green beans{80%grams}.

Stir the garlic and the @korma curry paste{50%grams} into the saucepan. Fry for 
~{1%minute} until fragrant.

Pour the @tomato passata{1%carton}, @vegetable stock paste{15%grams} and 
@water for the sauce{250%milliliters} into the saucepan. Stir in the chopped 
green beans.

Bring to the boil, then simmer until the sauce has thickened a little and the 
beans are tender, ~{8-10%minutes}.

When the sauce has thickened, stir in the @mango chutney{40%grams}. Add a knob 
of @?butter{} if you'd like to.

Stir the roasted potatoes into the sauce. Taste the sauce and season with 
@salt{} and @pepper{} if you'd like to.

Divide the stew between your bowls.

Top with the roasted curried cauliflower.

Swirl the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%grams} into the stew to finish.

> Kids Step: Use a spoon to swirl the yoghurt into your lagoon stew to make 
> some waves!

Enjoy!